1.3 Functions

 

Exercise 1

a) We first prove that ∀x∈X,∃y1∈Y ((x,y1)∈R1∧(y1,x)∈R2). This establishes existence of the image of x in Y. We will then prove that if ∃(x,y2)∈R1, then y1=y2, thereby establishing uniqueness of the image of x in Y.

  • x∈X ⟹(x,x)∈ΔX ⟹(x,x)∈R2∘R1 ⟹ ∃y1∈Y((x,y1)∈R1∧(y1,x)∈R2).

  • Now, assume further that, (x,y2)∈R1. Then,

    ((x,y1)∈R1)∧((x,y2)∈R1)⟹(y1,x)∈R2)∧((x,y2)∈R1⟹(y1,y2)∈R1∘R2⟹(y1,y2)∈ΔY⟹y1=y2

The above arguments establish that R1 is functional. An exactly analogous argument can be used to establish that the relation R2 is also functional.

Furthermore, the above arguments of existence and uniqueness have also established that: ∀x∈X,∃!y∈Y such that (x,y)∈R1∧(y,x)∈R2.

Since R1 and R2 are both functions, say f1 and f2 respectively, it follows from the above result that:

(f2(f1(x))=x)∧(f1(f2(y))=y).

R1 and R2 therefore define mutually inverse mappings of X and Y.

b) Let R⊂X2.

  • (⇒) Suppose that R is transitive. The following reasoning proves that R∘R⊂R. (x1,x2)∈R∘R ⟹ ∃x3∈X((x1,x3)∈R∧(x3,x2)∈R) ⟹ (x1,x2)∈R. The first implication follows from the definition of R∘R. The second implication follows from the transitivity of R.

  • (⇐) Suppose that R∘R⊂R. The following reasoning proves that R is transitive. ((x1,x3)∈R∧(x3,x2)∈R) ⟹ (x1,x2)∈R∘R ⟹ (x1,x2)∈R. The first implication follows from the definition of R∘R. The second implication is true because R∘R⊂R.

c) Let R⊂X2.

  • (⇒) Suppose that R is antisymmetric. The following reasoning proves that R∩R′⊂ΔX. (x,y)∈R∩R′ ⟹ xRy∧xR′y ⟹ xRy∧yRx ⟹ x=y ⟹ (x,y)∈ΔX. The second implication follows from the definition of R′. The third implication is true because R is antisymmetric.

  • (⇐) Suppose that (f∘h=idY) ∧ ¬(f is surjective). The second condition tells us that ∃y∈Y,∀x∈X:(f(x)≠y). The first condition tells us ∀y∈Y:f(h(y))=y. But h(y)∈X. So we now have ∀y∈Y,∃x∈X:(f(x)=y). This contradiction establishes that the original assumption is false. Therefore, (f∘h=idY) ⇒ (f is surjective).

d) Suppose that (a,b) is an arbitrary element of X2. We have,

(a,b)∈R∪R′ ⟺ aRb∨aR′b ⟺ aRb∨bRa.

 

Exercise 2

a) For the mapping pr1:X1×X2→X1, the fiber over the singleton {x1}⊂X1 is defined by:

f−1(x1)={(x1,x)∣x∈X2}

Similarly, for the mapping pr2:X1×X2→X1, the fiber over the singleton {x2}⊂X2 is defined by:

f−1(x2)={(x,x2)∣x∈X1}

b) An element x1∈X will be considered connected with an element x2∈X by the relation R⊂X2, if x1 and x2 both lie in the same fiber. We verify that R is an equivalence relation.

  • Reflexivity: Each element trivially lies in the same fiber as itself. That is ∀x∈X(f(x)=f(x)). Hence, xRx.

  • Symmetry: ∀x1,x2∈X we have: f(x1)=f(x2) ⇒ f(x2)=f(x1). Hence, x1Rx2 ⟹ x2Rx1.

  • Transitivity: ∀x1,x2,x3∈X we have: f(x1)=f(x2) ∧ f(x2)=f(x3) ⟹ f(x1)=f(x3). That is, if x1 and x2 lie in the same fiber, and also x2 and x3 lie in the same fiber, then x1 and x3 lie in the same fiber. Hence, x1Rx2 ∧ x2Rx3 ⟹ x1Rx3.

c) Consider the fibers of a mapping f:X→Y.

  • The fibers of a mapping do not intersect one another. Indeed, suppose that the f−1(x1) and f−1(x2) intersect one another. Then, ∃x(x∈f−1(x1)∧x∈f−1(x2)). But then, f(x1)=f(x) ∧ f(x)=f(x2). Consequently, f(x1)=f(x2). In other words, f−1(x1) and f−1(x2) represent the same fiber.

  • The union of all the fibers is the whole set X. Let the set F be the union of all the fibers of the given mapping. x∈X ⇒ ∃y∈Y(y=f(x)) ⇒ x∈f−1(y) ⇒ x∈F. Hence, X⊂F. On the other hand, F⊂X follows from the definition of fiber.

d) Suppose that R⊂X2 is an equivalence relation between the elements of X. We now define the set [xi]={x∈X∣xRxi}. The sets [xi] (where i belongs to some indexing set I) have the following properties:

  • From reflexivity of the equivalence relation, it follows that every element of X belongs to some set [xi], and that each [xi] is non-empty.

  • Moreover, (x0∈[xi]) ∧ (x0∈[xj]) ⟹ (x0Rxi) ∧ (x0Rxj) ⟹ (xiRx0) ∧ (x0Rxj) ⟹ (xiRxj).

The first of the above arguments shows that the union of all equivalence classes [xi] is X, while the second argument shows that the [xi] so defined are disjoint.

 

Exercise 3

In the following, f:X→Y, is a mapping from X into Y. A and B are subsets of X, while A′ and B′ are subsets of Y.

a) Suppose that A⊂B.

  • y∈f(A) ⇒ ∃x∈A(y=f(x)) ⇒ (x∈B)∧(y=f(x)) ⇒ y∈f(B).

    Hence A⊂B ⟹ f(A)⊂f(B).

  • To prove that f(A)⊂f(B) ⟹⧸⟹ A⊂B, provide a counterexample.

    Counterexample-1

    f:R→{k}, where k is a constant, and A and B are any disjoint sets in R.

    Counterexample-2

    sin:R→[−1,1], where A=[−π,0] and B=[0,2π].

b) A≠∅ ⟹ x∈A ⟹ f(x)∈f(A) ⟹ f(A)≠∅.

c) y∈f(A∩B) ⟺ ∃x∈A∩B such that y=f(x) ⟺ (x∈A) ∧ (x∈B) ∧ y=f(x) ⟹ y∈f(A)∧y∈f(B) ⟺ y∈f(A)∩f(B).

Note

Contrast the above chain of reasoning (all equivalences except one) with the reasoning in the next problem (all equivalences).

d) y∈f(A∪B) ⟺ ∃x∈A∪B such that y=f(x) ⟺ ((x∈A)∨(x∈B)) ∧ y=f(x) ⟺ ((x∈A)∧(y=f(x))) ∨ ((x∈B)∧(y=f(x))) ⟺ y∈f(A)∪f(B).

e) Suppose that A′⊂B′. Then,

x∈f−1(A′) ⟹ ∃y∈A′ such that f(x)=y ⟹ ∃y∈B′ such that f(x)=y ⟹ x∈f−1(B′).

f) x∈f−1(A′∩B′) ⟺ ∃y∈A′∩B′ such that y=f(x) ⟺ (y∈A′)∧(y∈B′) ∧ y=f(x) ⟺ ((y∈A′)∧(y=f(x))) ∧ ((y∈B′)∧(y=f(x))) ⟺ x∈f−1(A′)∩f−1(B′).

g) x∈f−1(A′∪B′) ⟺ ∃y∈A′∪B′ such that y=f(x) ⟺ ((y∈A′)∨(y∈B′)) ∧ y=f(x) ⟺ ((y∈A′)∧(y=f(x))) ∨ ((y∈B′)∧(y=f(x))) ⟺ x∈f−1(A′)∪f−1(B′).

h) Suppose that Y⊃A′⊃B′. Then,

x∈f−1(A′∖B′) ⟺ ∃y∈A′∖B′ such that f(x)=y ⟺ ((y∈A′)∧(y∉B′)) ∧ y=f(x) ⟺ x∈f−1(A′) ∧ x∉f−1(B′) ⟺ x∈f−1(A′)∖f−1(B′).

i) In the solution of Exercise (h) above, replace A′ with Y and B′ with A′.

x∈f−1(CYA′) ⟺ ∃y∈CYA′ such that f(x)=y ⟺ ((y∈Y)∧(y∉A′)) ∧ y=f(x) ⟺ x∈f−1(Y) ∧ x∉f−1(A′) ⟺ x∈X∧x∉f−1(A′) ⟺ x∈CXf−1(A′).

j) x∈A ⟹ f(x)∈f(A) ⟺ x∈f−1(f(A)).

k) y∈f(f−1(B′)) ⟺ ∃x∈f−1(B′) such that y=f(x) ⟹ y∈B′.

 

Exercise 4

a) Let f:X→Y, and B′ be an arbitrary subset of Y. We will prove that f is surjective if and only if f(f−1(B′))=B′ for every set B′⊂Y.

  • (⇒) We observe that f(f−1(B′))⊂B′ is true for any f as proved in Exercise 3(k). Now suppose that f is surjective and proceed as follows:

    y∈B′ ⟹ ∃x∈f−1(B′) such that y=f(x) ⟹ y∈f(f−1(B′)).

    Therefore, B′⊂f(f−1(B′)).

  • (⇐) Suppose that f(f−1(B′))=B′ for every B′⊂Y. Then, in particular, the statement is true for B′=Y. Thus, Y=f(f−1(Y)). But f−1(Y)=X by definition. Therefore, we have Y=f(X), so f is surjective.

b) Let f:X→Y.

  • In Exercise 4(a) we have proved that f is surjective if and only if f(f−1(B′))=B′ for every set B′⊂Y.

  • From Exercises 5(a) and 5(b) together it follows that f is injective if and only if f−1(f(A))=A for every set A⊂X.

From the two statements above it follows that f is bijective if and only if

(f−1(f(A))=A)∧(f(f−1(B′))=B′)

for every set A⊂X and every set B′⊂Y.
